message: Wait, only 3 out of the 4 of us are here

Greetings, CW Pythonistas!
Lookout Python world! :-)
Token ex-Wisconsinite in the house. :)
I was wondering if you'd show up here.
When I finally caught up on Twitter.
So lets see. From the limited cyber-stalking I've done, it looks like we've got 4 Djangonauts. Curious what @ponderings & @jason_theilman use Python for.
@ponderings Also, your Gpages page has a broken link to http://www.pycs.net/sqr/ AFAICT.
Fun!

@daniellindsley I use Python for prototyping and learning. Came across Python at OreillyNet when I was looking to learn Perl and found the language that 'fit my brain' and learning style from interpretted prompt days of school days BASIC (TI & TRS-80 CoCo). I haven't shipped anything in Python but have prototyped some products I've shipped in it (Google Docs file transfer), and of test tools.
@daniellindsley Thanks, I gotta update that bio stuff. :)
@ponderings How long ago was that?
If we can't find any more local Python devs, we'll just have to create them.
And from what I've seen, it only takes a little Python experience to get 'em hooked, coming from C# or Java.
Ahhh, sorry I should have specified VB.NET. I'd hope that most VB6 devs have moved on.
We will have to convert some VB & PHP programmers. That's what most devs in this area are.
I actually don't mind C# too much. It's actually my favorite static typed language.
I see a good amount .NET and Java too.
Actually I was a C# dev until I was seduced by Python; so it definitely works!
I guess if I had to pick one, I'd probably try C# too.
Although, I will admit that Python freaked me out a bit at first by not having to declare variables. I thought I'd run into all kinds of problems. Never happened. :)
